commentBody:
@BeeJay

If you have Trader Joe’s, you’ve got it. 
And why not google an ingredient you don’t know.

@Alexa

The texture of natural peanut butter is thicker than the more processed peanut butter. You make a good point because the ingredient list doesn’t specify which type to use

If I decide to make this with natural peanut butter, I will expect that I might need to add some hot water a teaspoon at a time or so in order to make the sauce a pourable consistency

@Paula

Skip it, it will still be delicious

If your body can tolerate garlic, you might want to briefly fry some slices of it, but that takes an extra step of effort

@Julia

Use fresh noodles and cut the noodle package in half or into fourths to get shorter noodles. I just cut my noodles in half for this and it was very easy to eat. I like the idea of taking it to a picnic! 

Penne or does not appeal to me for this

@dale
It is healthier. Here's what Google told me.
It contains essential nutrients and antioxidants, including manganese, zinc, potassium, and calcium. Because it has a lower glycemic index than regular sugar, it causes less drastic blood sugar spikes when used in moderation.

@Noah Please explain the baking soda method for me. 
Thank you 
Dori

@Julie Thank you for the soaking tip on steel-cut oats. 

And, to chime in on other threads: There is a Reddit group that ridicules wacky recipe alterations; I think it’s called “I didn’t have eggs.” 

The moderators here do a good job of weeding out people like my father. He mostly stayed out of the kitchen, ruefully recalling his bachelor attempt at boeuf bourguignon: canned stew with vodka. It was what he had on hand.

@dn

How lucky you are that you’ve got home-grown green onions!

Sorry it’s maddening, but most of us buy our scallions in bunches at the store. There are usually around eight in a bunch of typically-sized scallions, in the stores I frequent. You’ll have to judge for yourself what you think a typical scallion is

@CRH- I, too used frozen broth and turkey meat (leftover from Thanksgiving) from the freezer. 
I misread that I was supposed to add the pesto so I didn’t do that until after the broth came to a simmer. I then added the meat and pasta at the same time- cooked for about 10 minutes.
Nice and I agree that only 3 meal servings- (perhaps 4 as a starter. )

@tomrely,
No apologies necessary for canned creamed corn.
Say it loud! I like creamed corn and I’m proud!

@Pamela S

Don’t stress! You got this. 
Not flaky. Malissa talks about what salts to use under the Tips section. Kosher is what I used.

@Chris
The oil-cured would give this a nice cool weather depth, like using Urfa chile vs. Aleppo.
My local co-op has Mina brand green Moroccan olives with preserved lemon - SO fabulous. Use the two together and you have the epitome of yin/yang olive perfection!

@my notes we used prosciutto in place of anchovies as I am severely allergic to them. The thinking was that prosciutto is salty and a fairly good option. We used about 4 slices that we chopped and added just before the pasta was added to the frying pan. 
This was an easy dinner but fairly bland. Did not taste the lemons at all. I did use chopped up tarragon, as I was harvesting my herb garden, and that was a winner. 
Would make again, perhaps using preserved lemons.

@Jannequin
Excellent points. My favorite plant based butter to use for baking and, in fact, all recipes, is Miyoko’s Plant Milk Butter. It comes in sticks, it has a great flavor and texture (low moisture), and it comes the closest of any plant based butter to browning. Importantly, it does NOT contain any palm oil!
As an aside, Miyoko’s also has the hands down best plant based cheeses. I especially love their hard block of vegan Parmesan.

@RosebudTX

Either way, but if you want it on all four sides, I suggest putting in two pieces going in opposite (perpendicular) directions. 

I suggest you watch her video. It will probably be helpful, but don’t worry too much, as this is a forgiving kind of recipe.

@Liz You can google recipe conversions for moving cake from one size pan to another. Sally’s Baking Addiction has a good summary here:

<a href="https://sallysbakingaddiction.com/cake-pan-sizes" target="_blank">https://sallysbakingaddiction.com/cake-pan-sizes</a>/

A lot of classic, comprehensive style cookbooks often have this info too, in the baking section.

@Jenski H great idea, my oven will be full at Xmas.
What temp and time for air fryer?
Thanks
